'''Kamunaobi no Kami''' (神直日神) is a {{ill|deity|ja|神 (神道)|12=draft|12=draft}} appearing in {{ill|Japanese mythology|ja|日本神話|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="T">[[Atsushi Yamakita]] ''Dictionary of Eastern Deities,'' {{ill|Shinkigensha|ja|新紀元社|12=draft|12=draft}}, p. 349.</ref> This deity is regarded as one who purifies defilements and rectifies calamities (禍, ''maga''). In the ''{{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft|12=draft}}'', the deity is referred to as '''Kamunaobi no Kami''' (神直毘神), while in the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft|12=draft}}'', it is written as '''Kamunaobi no Kami''' (神直日神). The name also appears as '''Kamunaobi no Kami''' (神直備神) in some texts.
== Overview == During the {{ill|birth of deities|ja|神産み|12=draft|12=draft}}, when {{ill|Izanagi|ja|伊邪那岐命|12=draft|12=draft}} returned from {{ill|Yomi|ja|黄泉|12=draft|12=draft}}, the defilements of the underworld gave rise to the deity {{ill|Magatsuhi no Kami|ja|禍津日神|12=draft|12=draft}}. To rectify the calamities caused by Magatsuhi no Kami, '''Kamunaobi no Kami''' was born as one of the {{ill|Naobi no Kami|ja|直毘神|12=draft|12=draft}}. Following this, a second deity, '''Ōnaobi no Kami''' (大直日神), was born, and finally {{ill|Izanome|ja|伊豆能売|12=draft|12=draft}} was born.
== Analysis == According to the scholar {{ill|Shinobu Orikuchi|ja|折口信夫|12=draft|12=draft}}, the following interpretations have been proposed:<ref name="U">[[Shinobu Orikuchi]], ''Collected Works of Shinobu Orikuchi (New Edition),'' {{ill|Chūōkōron-shinsha|ja|中央公論新社|12=draft|12=draft}}.</ref> * The ''Naobi'' deity was conceptualized as a counterpart to Magatsuhi no Kami, representing two sides of the same coin. The {{ill|Naobi no Kami|ja|直毘神|12=draft|12=draft}} is seen as the priest who performs purification rituals, while Izanome is considered a shamaness (miko). * The verb ''naoru'' (to correct or heal) is related to the "直" (nao) in ''Naobi no Kami,'' symbolizing a deity that corrects mistakes or restores balance. * During the {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, Naobi no Kami was revered as a deity of banquets and entertainment.
