[[Image:Descendants of izanagi alone.svg|thumb|right|200px|Deities born from Izanagi's purification ritual (based on the ''Kojiki'') [//upload.wikimedia.org/]]]
'''Kamunaobi no Kami''' (神直日神) is a {{ill|deity|ja|神 (神道)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} appearing in {{ill|Japanese mythology|ja|日本神話|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name="T">[[Atsushi Yamakita]] ''Dictionary of Eastern Deities,'' {{ill|Shinkigensha|ja|新紀元社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, p. 349.</ref> This deity is regarded as one who purifies defilements and rectifies calamities (禍, ''maga''). In the ''{{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'', the deity is referred to as '''Kamunaobi no Kami''' (神直毘神), while in the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'', it is written as '''Kamunaobi no Kami''' (神直日神). The name also appears as '''Kamunaobi no Kami''' (神直備神) in some texts.
== Overview == During the {{ill|birth of deities|ja|神産み|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, when {{ill|Izanagi|ja|伊邪那岐命|qq=draft|qq=draft}} returned from {{ill|Yomi|ja|黄泉|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the defilements of the underworld gave rise to the deity {{ill|Magatsuhi no Kami|ja|禍津日神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. To rectify the calamities caused by Magatsuhi no Kami, '''Kamunaobi no Kami''' was born as one of the {{ill|Naobi no Kami|ja|直毘神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Following this, a second deity, '''Ōnaobi no Kami''' (大直日神), was born, and finally {{ill|Izanome|ja|伊豆能売|qq=draft|qq=draft}} was born.
== Analysis == According to the scholar {{ill|Shinobu Orikuchi|ja|折口信夫|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the following interpretations have been proposed:<ref name="U">[[Shinobu Orikuchi]], ''Collected Works of Shinobu Orikuchi (New Edition),'' {{ill|Chūōkōron-shinsha|ja|中央公論新社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.</ref> * The ''Naobi'' deity was conceptualized as a counterpart to Magatsuhi no Kami, representing two sides of the same coin. The {{ill|Naobi no Kami|ja|直毘神|qq=draft|qq=draft}} is seen as the priest who performs purification rituals, while Izanome is considered a shamaness (miko). * The verb ''naoru'' (to correct or heal) is related to the "直" (nao) in ''Naobi no Kami,'' symbolizing a deity that corrects mistakes or restores balance. * During the {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Naobi no Kami was revered as a deity of banquets and entertainment.
== Major Shrines Dedicated to Kamunaobi no Kami and Ōnaobi no Kami == * {{ill|Kego Shrine|ja|警固神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – Fukuoka City, Fukuoka Prefecture * {{ill|Sakurai Shrine (Itoshima)|ja|桜井神社 (糸島市)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – Itoshima City, Fukuoka Prefecture * Naobi Shrine – Nogata City, Fukuoka Prefecture * {{ill|Hayasuihime Shrine|ja|早吸日女神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – Ōita City, Ōita Prefecture * {{ill|Saikanda Shrine|ja|西寒多神社|1=Sasamuta Shrine|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – Ōita City, Ōita Prefecture * Dewasanzan Shrine, Sanshin Gōsai-den – Tsuruoka City, Yamagata Prefecture * Gosen Hachiman Shrine – Gosen City, Niigata Prefecture * {{ill|Udo Shrine|ja|鵜戸神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, within the grounds of Kyūhashira Shrine – Nichinan City, Miyazaki Prefecture * Isonosaji Shrine – Yazu District, Tottori Prefecture * Ōhara Shrine, within the grounds of Sakurai Shrine – Ōnan Town, Shimane Prefecture * Noma Shrine – Imabari City, Ehime Prefecture * Kambe Shrine – Kōshū City, Yamanashi Prefecture * Ōagata Shrine, within the grounds of Kaijo Shrine – Inuyama City, Aichi Prefecture * {{ill|Ikasuri Shrine|ja|坐摩神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, within the grounds of Aiden Shrine – Chūō Ward, Osaka City * Ikuto Shrine – Toyooka City, Hyōgo Prefecture * {{ill|Ayato Kuninaka Shrine|ja|綾戸国中神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – Kyoto City, Kyoto Prefecture * {{ill|Itsukushima Shrine|ja|厳島神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – Hatsukaichi City, Hiroshima Prefecture * {{ill|Isonokami Shrine|ja|石上神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, within the grounds of Shichiza Shrine – Tenri City, Nara Prefecture
