[[Image:Descendants of izanagi alone.svg|thumb|right|200px|Deities born from Izanagi's purification ritual (based on the ''Kojiki'') [//upload.wikimedia.org/]]]
'''Kamunaobi no Kami''' (神直日神) is a [[:en:Kami|Deity]] appearing in [[:en:Japanese mythology|Japanese mythology]].<ref name="T">[[Atsushi Yamakita]] ''Dictionary of Eastern Deities,'' {{ill|Shinkigensha|ja|新紀元社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinkigensha|qq=}}, p. 349.</ref> This deity is regarded as one who purifies defilements and rectifies calamities (禍, ''maga''). In the ''[[:en:Kojiki|Kojiki]]'', the deity is referred to as '''Kamunaobi no Kami''' (神直毘神), while in the ''[[:en:Nihon Shoki|Nihon Shoki]]'', it is written as '''Kamunaobi no Kami''' (神直日神). The name also appears as '''Kamunaobi no Kami''' (神直備神) in some texts.
== Overview == During the [[:en:Kamiumi|birth of deities]], when {{ill|Izanagi|ja|伊邪那岐命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izanagi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to イザナギ}} returned from [[:en:Yomi|Yomi]], the defilements of the underworld gave rise to the deity {{ill|Magatsuhi-no-kami|lt=Magatsuhi-no-kami|lt=Magatsuhi no Kami|ja|禍津日神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Magatsuhi no Kami|qq=}}. To rectify the calamities caused by Magatsuhi no Kami, '''Kamunaobi no Kami''' was born as one of the {{ill|Ōnaobi no Kami|lt=Ōnaobi no Kami|lt=Naobi no Kami|ja|直毘神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Naobi no Kami|qq=}}. Following this, a second deity, '''Ōnaobi no Kami''' (大直日神), was born, and finally {{ill|Izanome|ja|伊豆能売|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izanome|qq=}} was born.
== Analysis == According to the scholar [[:en:Shinobu Orikuchi|Shinobu Orikuchi]], the following interpretations have been proposed:<ref name="U">[[:en:Shinobu Orikuchi|Shinobu Orikuchi]], ''Collected Works of Shinobu Orikuchi (New Edition),'' [[:en:Chuokoron-Shinsha|Chūōkōron-shinsha]].</ref> * The ''Naobi'' deity was conceptualized as a counterpart to Magatsuhi no Kami, representing two sides of the same coin. The {{ill|Ōnaobi no Kami|lt=Ōnaobi no Kami|lt=Naobi no Kami|ja|直毘神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Naobi no Kami|qq=}} is seen as the priest who performs purification rituals, while Izanome is considered a shamaness (miko). * The verb ''naoru'' (to correct or heal) is related to the "直" (nao) in ''Naobi no Kami,'' symbolizing a deity that corrects mistakes or restores balance. * During the [[:en:Heian period|Heian period]], Naobi no Kami was revered as a deity of banquets and entertainment.
